hat while its forms and issues evolved, the net amount of democracy remained stable over time.Elections in Oxford County, 1837-75 breaks new ground with its detailed treatment of the county's voice-vote method of election, which ended with the adoption of the secret ballot in 1874. Employing an idealized parliamentary democracy as an explanatory model, Emery captures both geographically specific details and general features of this era's electoral process to enrich current understandings of nineteenth-century Canadian democracy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aElectionszOntariozOxford (County)vCase studies. 0aElectionszOntariozOxford (County)xHistoryy19th century. 0aRepresentative government and representationzOntarioxHistoryy19th century. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Pre-Confederation (to 1867).2bisacsh1 aEmery, J.C. Herbert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144269909040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442699090423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442699090.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK